{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014WnqGBnnvpVqcnabnLpvgL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. I need to:\n\n1. Generate a new node certificate signed by the existing CA (from `/tmp/certs/ca.key` and `/tmp/certs/ca.crt` in the openssl-toolbox pod), valid for 1 year (~365 days)\n2. The SANs need to match the existing cert: `DNS:localhost, IP:127.0.0.1, DNS:crdb-cluster, DNS:crdb-cluster.cockroachdb, DNS:crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc, DNS:crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local, DNS:*.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local, DNS:crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local, DNS:crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.\n\nlocal, DNS:crdb-cluster-2.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`\n3. Update the `crdb-cluster-certs` secret with the new node.crt\n4. Restart the CockroachDB pods to pick up the new cert\n\nI'll work through this in the openssl-toolbox pod by creating an openssl config with the proper SANs, generating a new private key and CSR, then signing it with the CA.\n\nNow I need to sign the CSR with the CA to get a cert valid for 365 days, update the secret, do a rolling restart of the pods, and verify the new cert is in place. I think generating a fresh key pair is safer than reusing the existing one for this rotation.\n\nExecuting this in the openssl-toolbox pod...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":273,"cache_read_input_tokens":31447,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":273},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1f4b29b2-90cf-4236-829f-12849a333019","uuid":"a122259c-ca97-408a-97c2-14cc1a8053af","request_id":"req_011CcQJPx16CDLgZYKwWpDuV"}
